def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
JAVA=[
L(1,'What is Java?','Java is a powerful, object-oriented programming language used for Android apps, web servers, enterprise software, and more. Java code runs on the Java Virtual Machine (JVM), which means it works on any platform that has a JVM installed — "write once, run anywhere."','public class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println("Hello, World!");\n    }\n}','Every Java program must have a main method — it is the entry point where execution begins. All code lives inside a class.'),
L(1,'Compiling and Running Java','Java is a compiled language: source code (.java) is compiled into bytecode (.class) by javac, then the JVM runs the bytecode. The file name MUST match the class name exactly, including capitalization.','// Save as Main.java\n// Compile: javac Main.java\n// Run:     java Main\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println("Hello!");\n    }\n}','The filename must match the class name: Main.java contains public class Main. Getting the casing wrong causes a compilation error.'),
L(2,'Variables and Types','Java is statically typed — every variable must declare its type. Primitive types: int (integers), double (decimals), boolean (true/false), char (single character). String is a class (capital S), not a primitive.','int age = 25;\ndouble price = 9.99;\nboolean active = true;\nchar grade = \'A\';\nString name = "Alice";\n\nSystem.out.println(age);     // 25\nSystem.out.println(name);    // Alice','String starts with a capital S because it is a class. Primitives (int, double, boolean, char) are lowercase. This distinction matters in Java.'),
L(2,'Type Casting','Widening conversion (small to large type, e.g. int → double) is automatic. Narrowing conversion (large to small, e.g. double → int) requires explicit casting with parentheses and truncates the decimal part.','int x = 10;\ndouble y = x;       // auto: 10.0\nint z = (int) 9.7;  // manual: 9 (truncated!)\n\nString s = String.valueOf(42);   // "42"\nint n = Integer.parseInt("42");  // 42','(int) 9.7 gives 9, NOT 10 — the decimal part is truncated (dropped), not rounded. Use Math.round() for rounding.'),
L(3,'Operators','Java has arithmetic (+, -, *, /, %), comparison (==, !=, <, >), logical (&&, ||, !), and assignment (=, +=, -=) operators. Integer division truncates: 10 / 3 gives 3, not 3.33.','int a = 10, b = 3;\nSystem.out.println(a / b);   // 3 (integer!)\nSystem.out.println(a % b);   // 1 (remainder)\n\ndouble c = 10.0 / 3;        // 3.333...\nboolean result = (a > 5) && (b < 10); // true','Integer division drops the decimal: 10/3 = 3. To get 3.333, make at least one operand a double: 10.0/3 or (double)10/3.'),
L(3,'Increment and Ternary','Use ++ and -- for quick increment/decrement. The ternary operator (condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse) is a compact one-line if/else that returns a value.','int count = 0;\ncount++;  // 1\ncount--;  // 0\n\nint age = 20;\nString status = (age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Minor";\nSystem.out.println(status);  // Adult','x++ returns the old value THEN increments. ++x increments FIRST then returns. In expressions, this difference matters: int y = x++ gives y the old value.'),
L(4,'String Methods','Strings in Java have many useful methods: length(), charAt(), substring(), toUpperCase(), contains(), equals(), indexOf(), trim(). Always use .equals() to compare string content — not ==.','String name = "Hello World";\nSystem.out.println(name.length());       // 11\nSystem.out.println(name.charAt(0));      // H\nSystem.out.println(name.substring(0,5)); // Hello\nSystem.out.println(name.contains("World")); // true\nSystem.out.println(name.equals("Hello World")); // true','CRITICAL: Use .equals() to compare string VALUES. The == operator checks if two variables point to the same OBJECT in memory, not if the text is the same.'),
L(4,'String Formatting','Use String.format() or System.out.printf() to insert values into strings with format specifiers: %s for strings, %d for integers, %f for decimals. %.2f formats a decimal to 2 places.','String name = "Alice";\nint age = 25;\nString msg = String.format(\n    "Name: %s, Age: %d", name, age);\nSystem.out.printf("Price: $%.2f%n", 9.99);\n// Price: $9.99','Format specifiers: %s = string, %d = integer, %f = float/double, %.2f = 2 decimal places, %n = newline. These are used in printf and String.format.'),
L(5,'Arrays','Arrays hold a fixed number of items of the same type. Once created, their size CANNOT change. Elements are accessed by zero-based index. Accessing an invalid index throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.','int[] nums = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};\nString[] names = new String[3];\nnames[0] = "Alice";\n\nSystem.out.println(nums.length); // 5\nSystem.out.println(nums[0]);     // 1\n// nums[10] would throw an exception!','Use .length (no parentheses) for arrays. Use .length() (with parentheses) for Strings. This inconsistency trips up many Java beginners.'),
L(5,'Array Operations','Use Arrays.sort() to sort in place, Arrays.toString() to print an array as a readable string, and the enhanced for loop (for-each) to iterate without tracking indexes.','import java.util.Arrays;\n\nint[] nums = {5, 2, 8, 1};\nArrays.sort(nums);  // {1, 2, 5, 8}\nSystem.out.println(Arrays.toString(nums));\n\n// Enhanced for loop (for-each)\nfor (int n : nums) {\n    System.out.println(n);\n}','The for-each loop (for (int n : nums)) is cleaner when you do not need the index. Use a regular for loop when you need to know the position.'),
L(6,'If/Else and Switch','Use if/else if/else for conditional branching. Switch compares one value against multiple options. Java 14+ supports switch expressions with arrow syntax (→) that eliminates the need for break statements.','int score = 85;\nif (score >= 90) {\n    System.out.println("A");\n} else if (score >= 80) {\n    System.out.println("B");\n} else {\n    System.out.println("C");\n}\n\n// Modern switch (Java 14+)\nswitch (score / 10) {\n    case 10, 9 -> System.out.println("A");\n    case 8 -> System.out.println("B");\n    default -> System.out.println("C");\n}','Traditional switch requires break after each case — without it, execution "falls through" to the next case. Arrow syntax (->) avoids this issue entirely.'),
L(6,'Logical Operators','Combine conditions with && (AND — both must be true), || (OR — at least one true), and ! (NOT — inverts). Java uses short-circuit evaluation: if the first part of && is false, the second part is skipped.','int age = 25;\nboolean hasLicense = true;\n\nif (age >= 18 && hasLicense) {\n    System.out.println("Can drive");\n}\nif (age < 13 || age > 65) {\n    System.out.println("Discount");\n}','Short-circuit evaluation means: false && anything = false (skips right side), true || anything = true (skips right side). This prevents unnecessary computation.'),
L(7,'For and While Loops','Use for loops when you know the iteration count. Use while when the count depends on a runtime condition. Use break to exit early and continue to skip to the next iteration.','for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {\n    System.out.println(i);  // 0,1,2,3,4\n}\n\nint count = 10;\nwhile (count > 0) {\n    System.out.println(count);\n    count--;\n}','An infinite loop (while(true)) runs forever unless you break out. Forgetting to update the loop variable is the most common cause.'),
L(7,'Nested Loops and Do-While','Nested loops run the inner loop completely for each iteration of the outer. Do-while guarantees at least one execution because it checks the condition AFTER running the body.','// Nested: 3x3 grid\nfor (int row = 0; row < 3; row++) {\n    for (int col = 0; col < 3; col++) {\n        System.out.print("* ");\n    }\n    System.out.println();\n}\n\n// Do-while: runs at least once\nint x = 0;\ndo {\n    System.out.println(x);\n    x++;\n} while (x < 3);','Nested loop cost multiplies: 3 levels of 100 iterations = 1,000,000 operations. Be mindful of performance with deeply nested loops.'),
L(8,'Defining Methods','Methods are reusable blocks of code with a return type, name, and parameters. Use void for methods that do not return a value. All other methods must include a return statement.','public static int add(int a, int b) {\n    return a + b;\n}\n\npublic static void greet(String name) {\n    System.out.println("Hello, " + name);\n}\n\n// Call them:\nint sum = add(3, 4);  // 7\ngreet("Alice");       // Hello, Alice','Methods must declare a return type. void means no return value. int, String, boolean etc. mean the method MUST return that type.'),
L(8,'Method Overloading','Java allows multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists (different types or counts). The compiler picks the correct version based on the arguments you pass.','public static int area(int side) {\n    return side * side;  // square\n}\npublic static int area(int w, int h) {\n    return w * h;  // rectangle\n}\npublic static double area(double radius) {\n    return Math.PI * radius * radius;  // circle\n}','Overloading is determined by parameter types and count, NOT by return type. Two methods with same parameters but different returns cause a compile error.'),
L(9,'Classes and Objects','A class is a blueprint for creating objects. Each object has its own copy of the class fields (data). The constructor has the same name as the class, no return type, and runs when you use new.','public class Dog {\n    String name;\n    int age;\n    \n    public Dog(String name, int age) {\n        this.name = name;\n        this.age = age;\n    }\n    \n    public String bark() {\n        return name + " says Woof!";\n    }\n}\n// Dog d = new Dog("Rex", 3);','The this keyword refers to the current object instance. Use this.name to distinguish the field from the constructor parameter with the same name.'),
L(9,'Access Modifiers and Encapsulation','Control who can access fields and methods: private (same class only), protected (same package + subclasses), public (everyone). Make fields private and provide public getters/setters — this is encapsulation.','public class BankAccount {\n    private double balance;\n    \n    public BankAccount(double initial) {\n        this.balance = initial;\n    }\n    \n    public double getBalance() {\n        return balance;\n    }\n    \n    public void deposit(double amount) {\n        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;\n    }\n}','Encapsulation = private fields + public methods. This protects data from invalid modifications — deposit() can check that amount > 0 before changing balance.'),
L(10,'Inheritance','A child class inherits all public/protected fields and methods from a parent class using extends. Use super() to call the parent constructor. Use @Override to mark methods that replace the parent version.','public class Animal {\n    protected String name;\n    public Animal(String name) {\n        this.name = name;\n    }\n    public String speak() { return "..."; }\n}\n\npublic class Cat extends Animal {\n    public Cat(String name) {\n        super(name);\n    }\n    @Override\n    public String speak() {\n        return name + " says Meow";\n    }\n}','super(name) calls the parent constructor. @Override is optional but recommended — the compiler checks that you are actually overriding a parent method.'),
L(10,'Abstract Classes','Abstract classes define a template that child classes must complete. They CANNOT be instantiated directly. Abstract methods have no body — every non-abstract child MUST implement them.','public abstract class Shape {\n    abstract double area();\n    \n    public void describe() {\n        System.out.println(\n            "Area: " + area());\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Circle extends Shape {\n    double radius;\n    Circle(double r) { radius = r; }\n    double area() {\n        return Math.PI * radius * radius;\n    }\n}','You cannot do new Shape() — abstract classes cannot be instantiated. You MUST create a concrete child class that implements all abstract methods.'),
L(11,'Interfaces','An interface defines a contract: a set of method signatures that implementing classes must provide. A class can implement multiple interfaces (unlike extends, which allows only one parent class).','public interface Drawable {\n    void draw();\n    default void erase() {\n        System.out.println("Erasing");\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Circle implements Drawable {\n    public void draw() {\n        System.out.println("Drawing circle");\n    }\n}','Java 8+ interfaces can have default methods (with implementation). Classes can override them. Use interfaces when multiple classes share behavior but not data.'),
L(11,'Polymorphism','Polymorphism means objects of different classes can be treated as a common parent or interface type. The correct method version is called based on the ACTUAL object type at runtime, not the variable type.','Drawable[] shapes = {\n    new Circle(),\n    new Square(),\n    new Triangle()\n};\n\nfor (Drawable shape : shapes) {\n    shape.draw();  // calls correct version\n}','Polymorphism lets you write flexible code: the same method call (shape.draw()) does different things depending on what type of shape it actually is.'),
L(12,'Try-Catch Exception Handling','Java uses try/catch to handle runtime errors (exceptions) gracefully instead of crashing. The finally block always executes — whether an exception occurred or not. Catch specific exceptions first.','try {\n    int result = 10 / 0;\n} catch (ArithmeticException e) {\n    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());\n} finally {\n    System.out.println("Always runs");\n}','Catch the most specific exception type first, then broader ones. Catching generic Exception should be a last resort.'),
L(12,'Throwing Exceptions','Use throw to create and throw exceptions when invalid conditions are detected. Custom exceptions extend Exception (checked) or RuntimeException (unchecked).','public static void setAge(int age) {\n    if (age < 0) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\n            "Age cannot be negative");\n    }\n}\n\n// Custom exception\npublic class InsufficientFunds\n    extends Exception {\n    public InsufficientFunds(String msg) {\n        super(msg);\n    }\n}','RuntimeException subclasses (unchecked) do not need try/catch. Checked exceptions (extending Exception) must be caught or declared with throws.'),
L(13,'ArrayList','ArrayList is a resizable array from the Collections framework. Unlike fixed-size arrays, it grows automatically as you add items. Use generics <Type> to specify what type it holds.','import java.util.ArrayList;\n\nArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();\nnames.add("Alice");\nnames.add("Bob");\nnames.remove("Alice");\nSystem.out.println(names.size());    // 1\nSystem.out.println(names.get(0));    // Bob\nSystem.out.println(names.contains("Bob")); // true','ArrayList<String> uses generics to enforce type safety at compile time. You cannot accidentally add an Integer to an ArrayList<String>.'),
L(13,'HashMap','HashMap stores key-value pairs with fast lookups. Keys must be unique — adding a duplicate key overwrites the old value. Use get() to retrieve and put() to add entries.','import java.util.HashMap;\n\nHashMap<String, Integer> scores = new HashMap<>();\nscores.put("Alice", 95);\nscores.put("Bob", 87);\n\nSystem.out.println(scores.get("Alice")); // 95\nscores.remove("Bob");\n\nfor (var entry : scores.entrySet()) {\n    System.out.println(\n        entry.getKey() + ": " + entry.getValue());\n}','Use getOrDefault("key", 0) to return a default when the key does not exist. This avoids null checks and NullPointerException.'),
L(14,'Generics','Generics let you write type-safe code that works with any type. The type parameter <T> is replaced with an actual type (String, Integer, etc.) when you use the class. This catches type errors at compile time.','public class Box<T> {\n    private T value;\n    \n    public Box(T value) {\n        this.value = value;\n    }\n    public T getValue() {\n        return value;\n    }\n}\n\nBox<String> strBox = new Box<>("Hello");\nBox<Integer> intBox = new Box<>(42);','Convention: T = Type, E = Element, K = Key, V = Value, N = Number. These are just conventions — you can use any letter.'),
L(14,'Generic Methods and Bounds','Methods can have their own type parameters using <T> before the return type. Use extends to restrict which types are allowed: <T extends Number> only accepts Number subclasses.','public static <T> T findFirst(List<T> list) {\n    if (list.isEmpty()) return null;\n    return list.get(0);\n}\n\n// Bounded: only Comparable types\npublic static <T extends Comparable<T>>\n    T findMax(List<T> list) {\n    return Collections.max(list);\n}','<T extends Comparable<T>> means T must implement Comparable — this ensures you can compare items. Without bounds, T could be anything.'),
L(15,'Streams','Streams process collections in a functional style. Chain operations like filter(), map(), and forEach() to transform data. Streams are lazy — they only process elements when a terminal operation is called.','import java.util.stream.*;\n\nList<String> names = List.of(\n    "Alice", "Bob", "Charlie");\n\nnames.stream()\n    .filter(n -> n.length() > 3)\n    .map(String::toUpperCase)\n    .forEach(System.out::println);\n// ALICE, CHARLIE','filter() keeps elements matching a condition. map() transforms each element. collect(), forEach(), count() are terminal operations that trigger processing.'),
L(15,'Lambda Expressions','Lambdas are concise anonymous functions used with streams, event handlers, and functional interfaces. The syntax is (parameters) -> expression or (parameters) -> { body }. Method references (::) are an even shorter form.','// Lambda: sort by length\nList<String> words = new ArrayList<>(\n    List.of("banana", "fig", "apple"));\nwords.sort((a, b) -> a.length() - b.length());\n\n// Method reference (shorthand)\nwords.forEach(System.out::println);\n\n// Runnable with lambda\nRunnable task = () -> System.out.println("Run");','Method references like System.out::println are shorthand for lambdas that just call an existing method. They make code more readable.'),
]
